Play it Forward and donate that instrument laying around collecting dust! 🎷🎼🎺

As music instills teamwork and individual responsibility we do have students take band 5/6 grade. We are short on instruments in our classrooms and to help families we are holding an instrument drive. If your student has graduated or you still have yours and would like to donate it, you would be making a student very happy!

Music for all! From the littlest of children to the largest of instruments, we include all abilities and ages.

Feature Friday: Redhawk Music! 🎼

We wanted to feature our music department as there have been some changes. Ms. Carmody is now doing band in both Estelline and Hendricks and choir teacher, Mrs. Watt, from Estelline is heading up the choir in Hendricks. With this collaboration we hope to grow the instrument and vocal programs and work together as two schools.

As music instills teamwork and individual responsibility we do have students take band 5/6 grade. We are short on instruments in our classrooms and to help families we are holding an instrument drive. If your student has graduated or you still have yours and would like to donate it, you would be making a student very happy!

Music for all! From the littlest of children to the largest of instruments, we include all abilities and ages.

post_text:
Mask break! 😃

Let’s talk about these masks. While they are helping keep us safe, they can be irritating not only to wear but also to our skin. There is a new phrase coming out being coined as “maskne” or acne from the mask.

Let’s remember to keep our skin clean 🧼 and also wash 🧼 our masks regularly as they are carrying around plenty of germs. Think of it as another piece of clothing to throw right in the laundry.

2020 Youth Football Registration:
Please fill out the form linked below to sign your child up for the 2020 youth football season. This is more for numbers for the league. The form will close on August 5th. Registration will begin at 5:30PM and will be followed by the first practice at 6:00PM on August 10th. Additional forms are required, and will be posted on the group Facebook page. They will also be available at registration. The forms must be completed and turned in prior to your child participating in the first practice on August 10th. Please be sure to have your child bring a mouth guard and a water bottle to the first practice. The registration fee will be waived this year. However, we will still require the equipment deposit. If you have any additional questions or concerns please contact a Board Member or Coach.

- Aug. 4: Fall Sports Meeting (6:30pm) Please bring along athletic forms. Meeting will be in the big gym in Estelline.

- Aug. 6: HS Football Begins 🏈

- Aug. 10: JH Football Begins 🏈

- Aug. 13: VB and CC Begin 🏐 🏃 🏃🏻‍♀️

Note: This coming year's 6th graders are invited to play Volleyball on the junior high team and start on the first day Aug. 13.

Cheer:

Anyone interested in Football cheer this year should contact Molly Watt: 605-691-6138 or wattmolly@gmail.com.

Physicals:

Reminder for those going into 7th or 10th grade: You are due for a physical before participating in athletics for the 2020/21 season. 6th graders competing and practicing will also need a physical.

CDC guidelines allow for people within households to be together along the parade route, but encourage all others to maintain social distances of 6 feet or more.

post_text:
Someone needs to read the announcements every morning...WHY NOT YOU?

Reading morning announcements has become quite popular among the students. We all enjoy hearing the different voices and personalities each morning and what a confidence builder for the kids!

Some are nervous, some are excited, some need help with words, but in the end they are all learning a great skill in public speaking without actually standing in front of a group!

We are so proud they are taking the initiative!

post_text:
Groundhog Day ❄️ or 🌸
Super Bowl Sunday 🏈

There is so much going on but what about the date?

Today’s date is a rare eight-digit palindrome (reads the same, forward and backward), 02/02/2020 — the only one of its kind this century: The previous eight-digit palindrome like this was 11/11/1111, 909 years ago. We’ll only have to wait another 101 years for 12/12/2121. 😳

post_text: The 5th graders are learning about coral reefs in Mrs. Dorn’s science class! They were asked to use everyday materials to engineer artificial coral reefs that 1) were tall with lots of branches 2) could withstand strong ocean currents, and 3) could catch plankton. The results are impressive!

post_text:
First grade students read Mystery Vine by Cathryn Falwell.

Book description- As the seasons go by, the mystery vine grows and grows and grows. Now, finally, it is autumn, and the mystery vine is no longer a mystery. Hello, pumpkins!

At the end of the book there was a recipe for pumpkin apple bread. 🎃 🍏 🍞 Mrs. Lawburgh broke out the cooking utensils and had the students bake up some bread. It was delicious and everyone wanted seconds!

Recipe included at the end of the pictures! ☺️
text:
First grade students read Mystery Vine by Cathryn Falwell.

Book description- As the seasons go by, the mystery vine grows and grows and grows. Now, finally, it is autumn, and the mystery vine is no longer a mystery. Hello, pumpkins!

At the end of the book there was a recipe for pumpkin apple bread. 🎃 🍏 🍞 Mrs. Lawburgh broke out the cooking utensils and had the students bake up some bread. It was delicious and everyone wanted seconds!

Recipe included at the end of the pictures! ☺️

post_text: On Tuesday, students attended a presentation today at Lake Benton, along with other 3rd-6th grade students from Ivanhoe and Lake Benton, from the Science Museum of Minnesota on the topic of Engineering and careers related to it. Students got some hands-on learning experiences about how Engineering is a part of everything in our everyday lives. They also got to experience some problem-solving activities. In the pictures are Jaylin Carlson, Hunter Anderson, and Josias Pozzi, among other students from other schools.

post_text:
Looking for a new way of exchanging white elephant gifts? The 4th grade class rolled dice.

You have two sets of dice going around the circle. If you roll a pair you get to take a present from the middle or you can take a present from someone else (they are unopened). You keep playing for the time you choose. Once everyone has a gift, you open them up so everyone sees what they have. Then you play another round and steal the unopened gifts. 🎁

The students had a blast. Way to go Mr. Eide!
